---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import CodeExample from '../../components/CodeExample.astro';

const firstQuestionExample = `Ask first:
Does this make the system calmer,
or only make this ticket disappear?

Good CSS reduces future decisions.
Bad CSS creates new ones.`;
---

<DocsLayout
    title="Core Principles"
    description="The non-negotiable principles behind Layered Semantic CSS."
    schemaType="TechArticle"
>
    <section class="site-hero">
        <p class="eyebrow">Principles</p>
        <h1>The non-negotiables</h1>
        <p class="intro">
            These are the rules underneath everything else. If these stay true,
            the system stays healthy. If these drift, the architecture quietly
            becomes archaeology.
        </p>
    </section>

    <nav class="section-nav" aria-label="Principles sections">
        <a href="#first">Start first</a>
        <a href="#ownership">Ownership first</a>
        <a href="#layers">Layers before specificity</a>
        <a href="#selectors">Shallow selectors</a>
        <a href="#utilities">Utilities are exceptions</a>
        <a href="#hacks">Hacks are temporary</a>
        <a href="#tokens">Tokens before values</a>
        <a href="#calm">Calm CSS</a>
    </nav>

    <section id="first" class="content-block">
        <h2>Ask this first</h2>
        <CodeExample code={firstQuestionExample} language="text" />
        <p>
            Most architectural damage starts when short-term speed defeats
            long-term ownership. The first question should always be where this belongs.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="ownership" class="content-block">
        <h2>Ownership before selectors</h2>
        <p>
            Decide whether something belongs in base, layout, component,
            theme, utility, or hacks before writing selectors. Wrong ownership
            creates most bad CSS long before specificity joins the argument.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="layers" class="content-block">
        <h2>Layers before specificity</h2>
        <p>
            If styles are fighting, check layer order first. Do not reach for
            deeper selectors, IDs, or important declarations before checking
            precedence. Most specificity problems are architecture problems.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="selectors" class="content-block">
        <h2>Prefer shallow selectors</h2>
        <p>
            Components should use short, scoped selectors with obvious
            ownership. Deep selectors couple styling to markup structure and
            turn safe changes into archaeological digs.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="utilities" class="content-block">
        <h2>Utilities are exceptions, not architecture</h2>
        <p>
            Utilities are useful for accessibility helpers and truly universal
            patterns. If utility combinations keep repeating, they are probably
            a component asking to be named, not a permanent utility strategy.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="hacks" class="content-block">
        <h2>Hacks are temporary by definition</h2>
        <p>
            The hacks layer exists for urgent delivery needs, not permanent
            residency. If a fix will still exist in six months, it is probably
            a real architectural problem pretending to be temporary.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="tokens" class="content-block">
        <h2>Tokens before values</h2>
        <p>
            Spacing, colour, typography, and radius should come from tokens,
            not deadline-driven invention. Random values create design folklore,
            not maintainable systems.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="calm" class="content-block">
        <h2>Calm CSS beats clever CSS</h2>
        <p>
            Good CSS should feel boring. Predictable selectors, clear naming,
            obvious ownership, and fewer surprises matter more than cleverness.
            Future developers should not need detective work to ship safely.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2>Next useful pages</h2>
        <div class="hub-card-grid">
            <article class="hub-card">
                <h3><a href="/decision-trees/">Decision trees</a></h3>
                <p>Turn principles into repeatable day-to-day decisions.</p>
            </article>
            <article class="hub-card">
                <h3><a href="/contributing/">Contribution standards</a></h3>
                <p>Use these principles during pull requests and code reviews.</p>
            </article>
            <article class="hub-card">
                <h3><a href="/anti-pattern-gallery/">Anti-pattern gallery</a></h3>
                <p>See what happens when the principles get ignored.</p>
            </article>
        </div>
    </section>
</DocsLayout>
